<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18420131-847">
               <interp inst="t18420131-847" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18420131"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18420131-847" type="date" value="18420131"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18420131-847-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-847-18420131 t18420131-847-offence-1 t18420131-847-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>847. <persName id="def1-847-18420131" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-847-18420131" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-847-18420131" type="age" value="42"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-847-18420131" type="surname" value="LIGHT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-847-18420131" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">RICHARD LIGHT</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420131-847-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420131-847-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="sexual"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420131-847-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="bigamy"></interp> for bigamy.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1353" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1353" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1353" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1353" type="given" value="SUSAN"></interp>SUSAN HUGHES</persName>
                  </hi>. In 1823, I lived in the neighbourhood of Shrewsbury—I knew Mr. Eaton, of Claremont-buildings, there—the prisoner was in Mr. Eaton's service as footman—I remember in 1823, there was a young woman with whom he kept company, Emma Maria Fox—I knew her—the prisoner asked me to go to church with him and Emma Fox—I said, "I suppose you are going to be married?"—he said, "Yes"—I said, Ann Davis would rather go (Ann Davis is now dead) I did not go—the prisoner was often talking of his marriage, and so was Ann Davis too</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184201310195"></xptr>
               <p>—they were married at the church of St. Chad, at Shrewsbury—the prisoner told me so—he said the minister's name was Mr. Sandford—they afterwards went to live at her brother's, Richard Fox's, in New-street—they lived together as man and wife—I saw them together after, and they have been at our house together—I left the prisoner at Mr. Eaton's—I saw Emma Fox after the prisoner said he was going to church-—I saw her wedding-ring on the fourth finger—they lived together in Edom-place—I saw Emma Fox alive last Thursday four weeks, at Manchester.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know how long they lived together? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I saw Emma Fox at Manchester—she was living with her husband, whose name is Bell—she is married now—I went to see whether she was alive—Mr. Barnes sent me—he is an architect—she said she was very comfortable.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know whether she is married to Bell? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1354" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1354" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1354" type="surname" value="BARNES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1354" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BARNES</persName>
                  </hi>. I produce a copy of the register of marriage from St. Chad's, Shrewsbury—I examined it myself with the register of mar<lb></lb>riages—I am related by marriage to Margaret Turner Thompson—I pro<lb></lb>secute this case—I took this certificate down to Shrewsbury by order of Mr. Traill, and found the parish clerk—the register was open—I compared this copy with the book, and Mr. Webster did the same, and signed it—I will swear it is a true copy—(<hi rend="italic">reads</hi>)—"Richard Light, of this parish, bachelor, and Emma Fox, of this parish, spinster, were married in this church by banns, this 16th of July, 1823, by me, Thomas Landford, minister. "<hi rend="smallCaps">WILLIAM SPEAK</hi>,"</p>
               <p>In the presence of "<hi rend="smallCaps">ANN DAVIS</hi>. "</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Before you had obtained this, had you seen the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, on the 3rd of August, at my house—he made a state<lb></lb>ment to me, which I took down in writing at the time—he said he was married at St. Chad's on the 16th of July, 1823; that he married Emma Fox, a dress-maker, by whom he had three children, and one was dead; that he left his wife and two children in Manchester, that be had agreed to leave them, and never see them again—he stated that William Speak and Ann Davis were witnesses to the marriage, and that the clergyman was Mr. Landford.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you made him any promise that he should not be prosecuted? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I swear he made the state<lb></lb>ment without my giving him any inducement—I told him I should make use of the evidence against him—his third wife, Butler, was present.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1355" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1355" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1355" type="surname" value="YARROW"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1355" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE YARROW</persName>
                  </hi>. I am parish clerk of Shoreditch. I produce the register of marriages for that parish—I have the entry of a marriage of Richard Light with Margaret Turner Thompson—(<hi rend="italic">read</hi>)—"Marriage so<lb></lb>lemnized in the parish of Shoreditch, No. 268, 23rd November, 1837. Richard Light and Margaret Turner Thompson, both full age, bachelor and spinster, servants; Light living in New North-street, and Thompson in Well-street; and signed by them in presence of George Yarrow and Je<lb></lb>mima Trance."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1356" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1356" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1356" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1356" type="given" value="MARGARET TURNER"></interp>MARGARET TURNER THOMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I have known the prisoner since 1832—I went through the ceremony of marriage with him at Shoreditch church, on the 23rd of November, 1837—we were married by banns—he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184201310196"></xptr>
               <p>described himself as a single man—he lived two years and a fortnight with me, and then left me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How long had you known him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Since 1832—he lived at Crosby, five miles from Liverpool—he was living with Mrs. Luce, in George-square, Liverpool—we never lived in the same house together before we were married—I have lived in James-street, Buckingham gate—I was seduced by him, and clung to him till he married me—we lived together for two years before we were married—I lived with him because he promised me marriage.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1357" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1357" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1357" type="surname" value="WARNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1357" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE WARNER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City police-constable, No</hi> 325.) I took the prisoner on the 12th of December, in Lombard-court, Fleet-street—I found him on a roof of a house behind a stack of chimnies—I said I must take him—he said, "No, don't; go back, and say you can't find me"—I said I had been looking after him some time, and it was more than I dare do—I had a warrant to take him—he said, "I suppose it is about Margaret Tur<lb></lb>ner's marriage?"—I said, "Yes, you must go with me"—he still refused to come off the roof, and after persuading him some time I got hold of him by the collar—he said, sooner than he would go he would rather throw us both down, and break our necks—the distance was from thirty to forty feet—after some persuasion I succeeded in taking him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Could he not have brought you both down? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It would not have taken a great deal of trouble—he was alone on the roof.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18420131-847-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-847-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-847-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 42.</p>
